    "## Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We ask: How do production budget, movie genre, lead actors, language, and country of production influence a film's financial and critical success — measured by box office revenue and IMDb ratings — and does this relationship differ between US and non-US productions, and across the pre- and post-streaming eras (before and after 2015)? Specifically, we examine whether the budget-success relationship has weakened as streaming platforms have disrupted theatrical revenue models, and whether Hollywood's historically dominant global distribution network produces a stronger budget-revenue association compared to non-US film industries. We are also interested in whether lower-budget international films in certain genres can achieve comparable critical success (IMDb ratings) despite lower revenue, suggesting that financial and critical success are not always aligned. The key variables include production budget (numerical), genre (categorical), country of production (categorical), lead actor (categorical), original language (categorical), release year (numerical, used to define pre/post-2015 periods), box office revenue (numerical), and IMDb rating (numerical). We will use correlation analysis, group comparisons, and interaction-based statistical models to examine these relationships. This is an inferential data analysis task that builds on and extends prior work by incorporating geographic, temporal, and talent-related dimensions that the existing literature has largely overlooked.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The film industry is strongly influenced by production budgets, which affect everything from casting and visual effects to marketing and distribution. Different movie genres tend to require different levels of funding. Research on box office revenue prediction has confirmed that production budget is the single strongest predictor of a film's financial performance, with action and adventure genres consistently commanding the highest budgets while drama and horror operate at far lower cost levels.<a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1)\n",
    "\n",
    "Previous peer-reviewed work has also shown that genre plays a major role in determining production cost and financial outcomes. Shahid and Islam (2023) demonstrated that a genre's popularity at the time of release is a strong predictor of box office returns, and that drama films consistently carry lower budgets than action or adventure films — underscoring how budget and genre interact to shape financial outcomes.<a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>2</sup>](#cite_note-2)\n",
    "\n",
    "When it comes to critical success, the picture is different. A study analyzing IMDb user voting data found no significant correlation between production budget and average user ratings, suggesting that audience satisfaction is driven by factors such as storytelling quality and emotional resonance rather than spending alone.<a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>3</sup>](#cite_note-3) This supports our hypothesis that financial and critical success are not always aligned, and that lower-budget international films may achieve high ratings despite modest revenues.\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite this body of work, several important gaps remain. First, most existing studies treat the global film industry as a monolith and focus almost exclusively on Hollywood. However, industry data show that international revenues for US studio films now account for over 70% of Hollywood's total box office take, and that non-US industries operate under fundamentally different distribution conditions.<a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>4</sup>](#cite_note-4) Cross-national comparisons of how budget, language, and talent translate to success are therefore critical but largely absent from the literature.\n",
    "\n",
    "Second, few studies account for the structural disruption caused by streaming platforms. Research published in *Applied Economics* found that the launch of Netflix streaming in the US was associated with a 14–17% reduction in theatrical box office revenues, establishing a clear empirical link between streaming availability and declining theatrical performance.<a name=\"cite_ref-5\"></a>[<sup>5</sup>](#cite_note-5) This suggests that the budget-revenue relationship documented in pre-streaming studies may no longer hold post-2015, yet most prior analyses ignore this temporal shift. Our project directly addresses both gaps by incorporating country of production and original language as comparative variables, and by splitting our analysis across pre- and post-2015 time periods.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### References\n",
    "\n",
    "1. <a name=\"cite_note-1\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-1) Joshi, A., et al. (2024). Movie Revenue Prediction Using Machine Learning Models. *arXiv preprint*. https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.11651\n",
    "2. <a name=\"cite_note-2\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-2) Shahid, M. H., & Islam, M. A. (2023). Investigation of time series-based genre popularity features for box office success prediction. *PeerJ Computer Science*, 9, e1603. https://doi.org/10.7717/peerj-cs.1603\n",
    "3. <a name=\"cite_note-3\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-3) Wasserman, M., et al. (2014). Correlations between user voting data, budget, and box office for films in the Internet Movie Database. *arXiv preprint*. https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.3986\n",
    "4. <a name=\"cite_note-4\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-4) Follows, S. (2017). How important is international box office to Hollywood? *Stephen Follows Film Data and Education*. https://stephenfollows.com/p/important-international-box-office-hollywood\n",
    "5. <a name=\"cite_note-5\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-5) Walls, W. D. (2024). Is video streaming hurting box office revenues at U.S. theaters? *Applied Economics*, 57(44). https://doi.org/10.1080/00036846.2024.2387860\n"
   ]
  },
