    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We hypothesize that movies with larger production budgets, globally recognized actors, and English-language releases will generally earn higher box office revenue due to wider international distribution and marketing reach. Specifically, we expect this budget-revenue relationship to be stronger for US films than for non-US films, because Hollywood benefits from an established global distribution and marketing infrastructure that amplifies returns on high-budget productions — a network advantage that non-US industries generally lack.\n",
    "\n",
    "We further hypothesize that this budget-revenue association has weakened in the post-2015 period compared to the pre-2015 era, as the proliferation of streaming platforms has reduced audiences' dependence on theatrical releases, particularly for lower-budget films that would previously have relied on box office performance as their primary revenue source.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, we expect IMDb ratings to remain largely independent of production budget regardless of country of production or time period, consistent with prior empirical findings showing no significant correlation between budget and average user ratings. We also predict that some lower-budget international films, particularly in drama or thriller genres, may receive disproportionately high IMDb ratings relative to their revenue — suggesting that critical success and financial success are not always strongly aligned.\n",
    "\n",
    "Among genres, we expect action, adventure, and fantasy films to show the strongest positive budget-revenue correlation, since these genres depend most heavily on spectacle and wide theatrical distribution to justify their investment, while drama and horror — genres that can succeed critically and commercially on low budgets — will show weaker or more variable correlations.\n"
   ]
  },
