    "### Data Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "We use two complementary datasets that together cover the variables needed to address our research question. Both datasets contain information on production budget, genre, country of production, and financial/critical success metrics. Dataset 1 provides IMDb scores and gross revenue with a focus on the 1986–2016 period, while Dataset 2 extends coverage through 2017 and adds variables such as original language, cast, and popularity score. Together they allow us to examine how budget, genre, language, talent, and geography jointly relate to a film's financial and critical success, and how these relationships differ across the pre- and post-2015 streaming eras.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Combining the datasets:** We merge the two datasets on movie title and release year after standardizing column names. Since Dataset 1 contains IMDb score and gross revenue and Dataset 2 contains popularity and additional cast/language detail, the merge produces a richer combined dataset. Rows that cannot be matched are retained in their source dataset for separate analysis rather than discarded, to maximize sample size.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Dataset #1**\n",
    "  - Dataset Name: Movie Industry (Daniel Grijalvas)\n",
    "  - Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/danielgrijalvas/movies/data\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 6,820\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 15\n",
    "  - Key variables relevant to this project:\n",
    "    - `budget`: production budget in USD. Ranges from \\$218 to \\$300M. Some entries are zero or missing, indicating unreported budgets.\n",
    "    - `gross`: total theatrical box office revenue in USD. Primary financial success metric.\n",
    "    - `score`: IMDb user rating on a 0–10 scale. Primary critical success metric.\n",
    "    - `genre`: primary genre classification. Each film has only one genre, which may oversimplify multi-genre films.\n",
    "    - `star`: lead actor or actress. Allows us to examine whether star power is associated with revenue or ratings.\n",
    "    - `country`: country of production. Key variable for our US vs. non-US comparison.\n",
    "    - `year`: release year. Used to define our pre/post-2015 split.\n",
    "    - `rating`: MPAA content rating (G, PG, PG-13, R).\n",
    "    - `runtime`: film duration in minutes.\n",
    "    - `votes`: IMDb vote count (post-release; excluded from predictive modeling, used in EDA only).\n",
    "  - Shortcomings: Missing/zero budget values for many films; coverage ends at 2016; single genre per film; IMDb scores may be biased toward popular Western films.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Dataset #2**\n",
    "  - Dataset Name: Movie Dataset: Budgets, Genres, Insights (Utkarsh)\n",
    "  - Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/utkarshx27/movies-dataset\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 4,802\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 24\n",
    "  - Key variables relevant to this project:\n",
    "    - `budget`: production budget (assumed USD; currency not explicitly stated — key limitation).\n",
    "    - `revenue`: total revenue earned. Comparable to `gross` in Dataset 1.\n",
    "    - `genres`: multiple genres per film — more nuanced than Dataset 1.\n",
    "    - `original_language`: language the film was primarily produced in. Critical for language-based analysis.\n",
    "    - `production_countries`: country or countries of production.\n",
    "    - `cast`: full cast list rather than just lead actor.\n",
    "    - `popularity`: composite audience interest/engagement score.\n",
    "  - Shortcomings: Currency units unspecified; zero/missing budget and revenue entries; data quality uneven for older films.\n"
   ]
